    {
      "@id": "https://incidentdatabase.ai/blog/incident-report-2026-february-march-april/",
      "@type": "TechArticle",
      "name": "AI Incident Roundup – February, March, and April 2026",
      "description": "Surveying new incident IDs added between the beginning of February and the end of April 2026. The 109 new incident IDs range from Incidents 1362 to 1470.",
      "about": {
        "@id": "https://incidentdatabase.ai/"
      },
      "abstract": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "This roundup surveys 109 new AI incident IDs (1362–1470) added to the AI Incident Database between February and April 2026. The batch reveals persistent synthetic-media fraud alongside a pronounced cluster of agentic AI incidents."
      },
      "articleBody": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The 109 new incident IDs range from Incidents 1362 to 1470. These records do not all describe events that occurred during the same three-month window. Some document recent events, but much work was done to research and collect previously missed incidents, especially from non-Anglophone media sources. During this period, searches were run in Southeastern European and Balkan news sources and fact-checking services. The previous roundup emphasized deepfake-enabled fraud as a default business model. That pattern remains visible here. Many scam-related incidents depend on local systems of trust. The same general scam template can operate across borders, but often draws on someone or something familiar in a local context to execute it. While deepfake scam incidents remain prominent in reporting, a pronounced cluster of agentic AI incidents is also visible."
      },
